The Higgs boson in detail
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson generated a great commotion last summer, and rightly so.
It is believed, in fact, that this boson is part of the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything that exists in the universe, nothing more and nothing less.
And what is more, it is the particle whose existence the standard model predicted: our best or "least bad" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter, which has not yet been observed empirically.
But it is not entirely clear to physicists that it is Higgs.
We know without a doubt that a new particle exists and that it closely resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the standard model.
In addition, new data unveiled this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seem to confirm that it is, although more data is still missing to be completely sure.
Anyway, we assume it's Higgs, since the chances of getting it wrong seem slim. We'll see what it's all about.
There is, in this great world, a widespread and inescapable law that implies that two things cannot be found in the same place at the same time.
There’s no way to break that rule and don’t try too hard, because you’ll end up hurting yourself.
Although particle physics is a very complex world, it has been shown that there is also a law of these characteristics: the Pauli exclusion principle, which stipulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state"; a "state" that consists, roughly, of some of their characteristics.
Physicists classify particles into two categories.
On the one hand we find the good citizens called fermions, who wisely obey the principle of Pauli.
And then there are the bosons, a dirty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything, or at least not for this principle, which means they can be found in the same place and at the same time.
According to the Berkeley Labs website The Particle Adventure, which, by the way, is extraordinary, bosons are divided into two groups: the mesons, which we won't talk about here, and the "force particles," by which the great forces of nature propagate and with which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, it could be emphasized here, are not the exotic bugs we might believe.
In fact, if he manages to read this chronicle, it is thanks to an extraordinarily banal boson: the photon or "particle of light" that acts as a "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
Indeed, when a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it “disorders” the electromagnetic field in that precise environment; a bit like when we throw a stone into a pond.
In this "disorder" is born an electromagnetic wave (of light, infrared, ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon; that is, one of the "force-carrying" bosons.
More stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which needs to be "disordered" for this boson to appear.
However, the Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field. To activate it you need to reach extremely high energies, a bit like an icy pond in which only a thick rock could slide on the surface.
That’s why it takes an immense particle accelerator like CERN’s (the big hadron collider is a 27-km-circumference ring!) to reach such energy levels.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is a new tool that explains the relationship between the Higgs and mass.
In fact, not all particles or materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others do not: a piece of paper, for example, will never by itself stick to the door of a refrigerator.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have a mass, while the rest (like the photon, by the way), do not.
Now, what "can all these investigations contribute?", Mrs Plamondon asks.
For science, this serves to verify the validity of the Standard Model (SM), and also allows physicists to scrutinize the differences between the observations and predictions of the SM.
For their part, many fervently want them to meet, because the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physics" that covers certain holes in the model.
This, it must be said, still has enormous shortcomings, as it does not propose any explanation related to gravity (ups!) or dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the matter in the Universe (another ups!).
But we haven’t found such differences at CERN so far.
Implications
The repercussions of such research on our day-to-day lives are hard to predict, but we don’t think we’re wrong to say that it won’t have any.
In the early 1960s, the pioneers of lasers in laboratories had absolutely no suspicion of the revolution their work would bring about.
They envisioned scientific applications, but nothing more.
In fact, as physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Laboratories, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed) in 1962, said, at first the laser was rather considered a "laboratory apparatus".
Just imagine...
And in addition, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the research.
For example, Willard Boyle himself developed a light-gatherer in 1969 in the course of his research into optics.
Although it was not at all his original intention, this pickup now serves as an "eye" for all the digital devices in the world, which earned him the Nobel Prize in physics in 2009.
This does not mean, of course, that the activities of the LHC necessarily want to transform our lives, but that we never know...
Palliative care. The best way to die...
In its Dying in Dignity Commission, Quebec recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate should resume soon while a bill is being prepared.
Now, within that essential domain, there is still much to be done.
Le Devoir tried to see him up close.
Just a few weeks ago, Mr. L. lived alone in his Montérégie apartment.
The prostate cancer that was destroying him had given him a two-year respite.
“They had given me five years to live, but I’ve already been like this for seven years,” he says, lying in his bed in the Victor-Gadbois palliative care center in Beloeil, where he arrived the day before.
“But it’s always a shock, we can’t be prepared for this,” he continues.
The disease has wreaked havoc on him: a huge weakness that prevents him from going to the bathroom alone and even eating on his own.
Sitting in front of an appetizing lunch, he resignedly accepts to be helped to eat.
Brave, he even smiles, talking to strangers who give him attention, bring him medicine and offer him a bath.
The courage of ordinary death.
“My biggest wish is to be cured of diarrhea, it’s humiliating,” he confesses.
A few hours later, the team found a cure.
“In the course of our lives we learn that a man pees on his feet,” says Pierre Brodeur, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois center.
Going back to their childhood, for some people, is an unacceptable humiliation.
“That depends on the person’s ability to accept that regression,” he says.
Because, in the opinion of most people who work in palliative care, the big moments take place at the very heart of that regression.
All patients entering the Victor-Gadbois Palliative Care Center have cancer.
They have a maximum life expectancy of three months.
In that state, the team of doctors and nurses around them no longer offer “curative” care.
Ms. A., 89,’s greatest fear is to die “conscious and drowned.”
But the disease has made her discover her children.
“I have good children,” he adds.
“I have no more desires left in this life,” she says, before agreeing to have a mask put on to help her breathe.
And he expects, in the coming days, a last visit from his son who lives in Italy.
In Victor-Gadbois is offered, with a group of volunteers, body care and food aid.
They are palliative care that is given when nothing else can be done.
To help make his death more comfortable.
In Quebec we have a palliative care bed for every 11,700 inhabitants.
It is very little, since we know that we will all end up dying one day.
Here, life continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christiane Martel, one of the doctors at the center.
Whether at the level of physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
The dying man is offered brandy or Pepsi mouthwashes, according to the lawsuit.
Diabetics are no longer in control of their sugar levels.
Death is part of everyday life.
Last night we served a beer to Mr. X, who died in the course of the night.
This morning, his son finished his beer at the feet of the deceased.
“We help both patients and their loved ones,” says Nathalie Savard, director of care.
At the Victor-Gadbois centre, the days go by without ever being the same.
Beside a 94-year-old man savoring his last family reunion in the courtyard, well placed between his pillows while everyone drinks to his health, a 36-year-old tragically dies, surrounded by his parents, his wife and their two children, after having tried everything to survive.
“For the past six months, there have always been three to five beds occupied by people under the age of 45 with cancer,” Dr. Christiane Martel said.
53% of patients who are admitted to the Victor-Gadboisarrivent center come from home and 47% from the hospital.
Access to palliative care
77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, care designed to alleviate suffering when a patient reaches the terminal phase of their life, whether at home, in the hospital or in a care facility.
And several agencies, such as the Victor-Gadbois Center and the Greater Montréal Home Palliative Care Society, specialize almost exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is precisely this relative lack in health care in Quebec that makes many doctors specializing in palliative care fear the adoption of a law that regulates euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto signed by eminences of palliative care, such as Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapointe, has been circulating to demonstrate their opposition to such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christiane Martel, Quebec’s health system is not competent enough to ensure that anyone is entitled to quality palliative care before euthanasia is accepted.
"Recently," he says, "I saw a patient spend 14 days in the ER suffering great pains without having done what was necessary to relieve her.
I fear that patients may wish to die just because they are not receiving the proper care.”
And at the same time, many oncologists are obstinate with their patients until the last day, despite the worst prognosis.
Hél<0xC3><0xA8>ne Richard’s hopes of survival were already at an all-time low when she left a grueling chemotherapy treatment.
“When I told my oncologist that I wanted to stop the treatment, she told me that she was very sorry that she wanted to stop fighting,” he says.
"However, she had told me there was nothing else to do!"
There is no almighty care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who request to die thank their caregivers for not attending to their demands once their pain has been relieved thanks to a palliative care team.
But it must be said that palliative care is not absolutely all-powerful when it comes to the treatment of pain.
According to Elsie Monereau, director of palliative care at home in Grand Montréal, patients do not respond to pain treatments in 8% of cases.
At the end of life, doctors usually resort to palliative sedation, which serves to sleep the patient until the moment of his death, either sporadically or permanently.
We can’t pretend that we don’t understand that part of suffering.
Increasingly, the unrelieved disease is going to have the possibility of having that palliative sedation.
The sick who are not relieved all say the same thing: "I want to die."
But that doesn’t necessarily mean “I want euthanasia,” but “I want relief.”
