A constitution with forceps in Egypt
It is a new double or nothing from President Mohammed Morsi.
While Egypt is more divided than ever about the constitutional declaration, which provisionally grants him full powers, he decided to play the whole for the whole.
It caught everyone by surprise on Wednesday, when it announced that the Constituent Assembly would vote on its final text the next day.
Just one week ago, the Head of State had given the Assembly two more months to complete its work.
And for almost two years Egypt has been using a provisional text, several times modified, which weakens institutional stability and leads to judicial entanglements.
This new initiative has only increased the fracture in the country.
For his opponents, the president perseveres in his “autocratic delirium” and continues “betraying his word” and “trampling on the law.”
Supporters say it is a move to end the institutional and political crisis faster and speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held in the next 15 days.
A very short period of time that forces the Brothers to give up their project of explaining the text, article by article, to the Egyptians.
For the president, it is also a way to regain popular and democratic legitimacy while the controversy wreaks havoc throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in his favor, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
Considering that this resource has been voted on very quickly, it contains an ultimatum for the Egyptian people: "either vote on my text or I keep the full powers", powers that will supposedly come to an end with the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in that strange environment that 85 members of this largely Islamist Constituent Assembly voted on the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not attend the meeting.
In mid-November, a little before the constitutional declaration, they had closed the door because they felt that they could not assert their views.
Representatives of human rights, religious minorities and civil society did the same.
In order to achieve the necessary quorum, 11 substitute members were added in a hurry yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
As expected, the articles voted on unanimously.
The commentators are amused, on the other hand, by the fact that one of the few discrepancies of the day has been expressed practically at the time of prayer, so much so that several members of the committee came to think that the clock of the Constituent Assembly was wrong.
The text, which was still being voted on yesterday afternoon, consists of 234 articles.
Article 2, the subject of all eyes, remains ultimately identical to that of the 1971 Constitution, which stipulated that “the principles of Sharia constitute the principal source of law”.
Salafist parties, for whom the establishment of Islamic law is a fundamental demand, hoped that “principles” could be replaced by “norms”, which would have allowed for stricter enforcement.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been amended is a guarantee of their goodwill and respect for the other components of Egyptian society.
Liberals call it hypocrisy and consider it nothing more than an advertising ploy.
According to them, the Islamization of the Constitution is done through other articles.
They refer, in particular, to article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, in particular for anyone who has to confirm its conformity with the laws of Sharia.
According to Egypt specialist Sophie Pommier, it is disturbing because "the people called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
Here we glimpse the premises of a theocracy.”
The liberals’ fears are further heightened by the fact that the next rector of that university would be much less moderate than the current one.
“For now, there is no concrete religious involvement.
With this Constitution we are in the framework of the civil status.
Most of the jurists who have worked on that text are not ulemas but university students, some of them trained in the French system,” explains Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a thesis on the Egyptian constitutional transition.
But he acknowledges that there may be some ambiguity around Article 220, as the terms used mimic the religious vocabulary.
"We are referring specifically to the term iqh [Islamic jurisprudence, ed.].
And the question that might arise in the future would be to what extent are the civil judges competent to rule above all this.”
Beyond its religious character, the text voted yesterday has received many criticisms that refer to the extended powers it confers on the president of the Republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood will claim that they are few in comparison to those who were during the previous regime.
Another point of contention: the powers vested in the army.
According to the wish of the military, the revision of the defense budget will not be submitted to Parliament, but to a national defense council.
Nor will the prosecution of civilians in military courts, as requested by associations for the defense of human rights, be prohibited.
They also expressed their concerns about the text, which they consider to be a liberticide.
The crime of blasphemy remains and, from now on, insults are prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially that of the press.
In addition, no articles emphasize the protection of women, Human Rights Watch’s Heba Morayef said.
According to her, the only positive thing has been the prohibition of torture under article 36.
The word did not appear in the previous Constitution.
Although the Egyptian president was supposed to go out last night on television, demonstrations are planned for this noon.
Supporters of the head of state demonstrated on Saturday.
