‘The Great and Powerful’ Will Take You to Moscow: Immigrants Save for Language
While deputies and human rights defenders argue about the consequences that the law would bring on the mandatory examination, scammers have already appeared in the country who trade with "false" certificates.
Every year, 13 million migrant workers arrive in Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asian countries: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan and Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn money to help their families who have stayed at home.
From December 1, a law comes into force, according to which every working immigrant must take an exam to check his knowledge of the Russian language.
For now, this rule applies only to those who intend to work in the service delivery sector, community service institutions, household services and retail trade.
However, over time, as promised in the Federal Immigration Service, exams will become mandatory for all immigrants.
In addition, it will not be enough to take the examination of the language, but also that of Russian history and that of the foundations of legislation.
Knowledge of the language must be confirmed even to receive and renew the work permit.
The exception is citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Persons who succeeded in obtaining their education certificates and diplomas before the dissolution of the Soviet Union in 1991 shall not be subject to this law.
Usefulness, fatality and defense of rights
The network of examination centres will operate under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of Russian Language, Peoples' Friendship University, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg State University and other Russian higher education institutions.
Immigrants will be able to take the tests in all cities, right now in Russia more than 160 such centers are open.
The initiative on the introduction of the examination was supported by the deputies of the State Duma and the Federal Immigration Service.
But rights advocates, long before the law went into effect, often managed to ask the press this question: And what will this actually bring?
What changes will the mandatory knowledge of the language bring, both for Russians and for immigrants themselves?
In the first place, respond representatives of the Immigration Service, this will reduce the number of people who suffer "labour slavery".
Many people today talk about defending the rights of working immigrants, explains Victor Sebelev, head of the representation of the Russian Federal Immigration Service in Tajikistan.
The defense of your rights must begin before your departure.
Only an organized selection system will solve the problem of immigrant workers in 90% of cases.
The problems are those immigrants without profession, education, those who do not know the language or pass the medical control.
Without understanding the language, Sebelev says, the future immigrant will be doomed to find unscrupulous people who, under the guise of helping, put a “paid trip” into a creepy, narrow-minded brood, where he and dozens of others like him are consumed for months without food or documents, working 12 to 14 hours a day.
We received countless complaints from our immigrants.
“In their homeland they are promised one thing, but when they arrive they are deceived, they are deprived of their passports, they are not paid the promised salaries,” confirms the Head of the Directorate of Labour Immigration of the Immigration Service of Tajikistan, Tolib Sharipov.
Don't get mad, boss boy!
Meanwhile, however, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who wish to work in Russia recognize that they not only do not know the language of the country they intend to go to, but also write with difficulty in their own language.
Of course, this is not so much their fault but their own misfortune: few Turkmen, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to receive normal primary education.
This is because their families don’t even have anything to feed the children, let alone dress them, shoe them, and buy them what they need for school.
Arriving in adolescence, these guys venture to work at the first opportunity.
It is difficult, if you do not know the language, recognize them.
“One feels humiliated and inferior.”
However, when it comes to the language law, rights advocates point to an important point.
The exams will be held only for those immigrants whose status is legal.
If they do not have that status, there will be no examination and, consequently, no official work.
Meanwhile, the majority of migrant workers continue to live in Russia illegally.
"Welcome or forbid passage to strangers"
Many visitors claim that receiving official status in our country is not so easy.
The cause is bureaucratic obstacles and the difficulties of the language itself.
In addition, legalization costs money: from twelve thousand to sixteen thousand rubles.
However, a false inscription can be made quickly and for only fifteen hundred rubles.
The employees of the Russian police know that we usually carry false documents, we are not registered and extortion cases appear.
"They ask us for a hundred or two rubles for cigarettes or tea," Tajik citizen Umed Hushkadamov told reporters.
"Come on, don't be stingy, buy a painting."
On the first day of the entry into force of the language law, it became clear that not only immigrant registration documents can be false.
Several "false" certificates of knowledge of the language have already been seized by officials of the Federal Immigration Service.
The forged documents had been printed on standard colour printers.
Of course, they came into the hands of the new owners not as a gift: each immigrant, wanting to facilitate the task of passing the tests, paid for the document seven thousand rubles.
This is two and a half times more expensive than the official examination procedure, which will cost the immigrant worker three thousand rubles.
The main task for the near future is to protect the system against corruption so that “diplomas” cannot be bought, government officials and rights advocates converge.
So far, the authorities can promise immigrant workers that they would not have been able to successfully pass the exam the first time more time to study the basic language course.
In addition, immigrants who do not speak Russian will be offered jobs that do not require active communication with people.
