Is it an office similar to our NK<0xC3><0x9A> or is it organized in another way?
As for the offices, such as the NK<0xC3><0x9A>, where the Bundesrechnungshof (Federal Court of Accounts) operates, with an organization similar to ours, with a college too, the only thing is that in its case it is structured in a somewhat different way, but in principle both offices evolve in parallel.
The competences are also somewhat analogous, however, as far as Germany has a federal organisation, the courts of auditors are even at this level. In this respect it differs slightly from our system.
The Federal Court of Auditors (FCA) can only control federal money, which here we call state funds.
Public funds, which are administered by the regions and municipalities, there, in Germany, are controlled in the Federal Court of Auditors.
In terms of local legislation, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to make a comparison without concrete data. However, Germany remains a model in some respects, but it is not possible to specify exactly what is better.
Could it be better, for example, in terms of the quality of inspectors?
I'm sure not, but, I repeat, I don't like to make such comparisons.
Needless to say, even those countries we take as a model have to deal with a large number of problems.
If they didn't, it wouldn't be of any benefit to them to collaborate with our office, would it?
With regard to the legislation of our country, what did the amendment of the law on public awards mean for your Office?
Given that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been manifested in the control actions.
Since we carry out ex-post checks, there must be a certain delay.
For now, it is observed in the process of preparation of future controls: we have started a new tool of "detection of non-economic risks", through which we have passed almost 14,000 public awards, which have been analyzed. The changes will be perfectly reflected here, as the limits are modified, the conditions of some types of the selection process are rectified and the like.
Do you consider that the approval of this law is beneficial or that, rather, it is a mess for the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is surely a step in the right direction and I hope it is.
The problem that can arise is that the regulations are "hardened" and it is impossible to comply with them.
Already with the previous regulations, the controlled persons were linked to the contractor (for example, in the case of the regional operational programmes of the regional council), and every law not respected in the matter of public awards meant the violation of budgetary discipline.
Does it make sense then to harden the law in this way?
I don't think so.
The system must exclude those who want to attack or take advantage of it and not punish those who make a formal ruling, which has no bearing on decision-making.
Such a system will only create more bureaucratic pressure.
And how do you get out of this?
We will see where this initiated path leads us.
The Prime Minister has recently stated that the SDGs would not bother entrepreneurs with controls of the so-called <0xC5><0xA1>varc system, with reference to the fact of being autonomous only on paper.
Is the <0xC5><0xA1>varc" system prohibited or allowed?
The law must be regulated in some way and, if it prohibits something, then not even the prime minister of the government can prevent the action of the Office that has the obligation to carry out such checks and demand obligations.
You can say, “We change the law and we allow it,” but you can’t say we’re going to act like it.
In the law on public awards, the rules are quite strict as to how formal action should be taken, and that is how it should be in order to protect public competition.
But, on the other hand, it is tragic that the candidate with the best offer is excluded for not meeting the formal requirements.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct. This is, in my opinion, what we lack.
