Argo Movie: If It Gets Raw, Call Hollywood
In November 1979 a group of Islamist student protesters occupied the American embassy in Tehran and took 52 graduates hostage.
His release was to be in exchange for the dethroned Shah Mohamed Reza Pahlevi, who after the revolution fled to the US, a country that had sponsored his regime for decades.
For the American administration, the situation offered no positive perspective: throwing the shah overboard could not be allowed to do so, since, if it did, it endangered the confidence of its allies in other countries.
But the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution had led to the constitution of the theocratic regime, was not within their reach.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which subsequently intensified further with the failed attempt to free the hostages by force.
The imprisoned diplomats were released 444 days after the Algerian government’s negotiating intervention.
In the US, their fate caused a wave of solidarity and animosity against Iran.
The failure in Iran contributed decisively to Jimmy Carter's defeat by Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film "Argo" by director and actor Ben Affleck thematizes an episode of this story, which garnered a small success for America.
Shortly before occupying the embassy, six employees escaped from the building.
After a complicated journey, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian embassy.
The CIA, in collaboration with Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, for which a cover story helped an extravagant point: they left with Canadian passports, as members of the film team that examined the location in the country for the filming of a sci-fi blockbuster.
Combination of genres
The plan outlined by “exfiltration” expert Toni Mendez required Hollywood collaboration.
To make the lie seem truthful, it was written about the film project in specialized magazines, press conferences were organized, the fictional production company even had a real office.
Details about the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film has been made from the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck’s film is a singular combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a realistic political thriller; on the other, a so-called "caper movie", the story of an episode that went well, a hoax (an example can be the series Ocean's Eleven).
In the film, moods are combined. On the one hand, we find well-documented sequences from Tehran. In the sequence of credits, emblematic photographs of the time of the events are shown, which were captured in the same way in the film; there are not many differences in this regard.
On the other, typical Hollywood scenes somewhat lighter, marked by irony and a slight exaggeration.
And besides, scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions: dressed men analyzing the situation at the negotiating table, in the corridors of the office, by phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to restart his career in an excellent way.
The actor, who had been the object of ridicule, has become a respectable director and his way of acting has ceased to be the target of ironic comments.
Argo is his third feature film, after "Adi<0xC3><0xB3>s peque<0xC3><0xB1>a, Adi<0xC3><0xB3>s" (2007) and the thriller "The Town. City of Thieves" (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film in which the action has no place in the city of Boston, where he was raised.
Also, the sensitivity of capturing the atmosphere of the place was a feature that placed the directors of old films above Hollywood standards.
And Affleck proves it in Argo, where Tehran "wheels" in Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of the true events. The introductory sequence of the taking of the embassy is impressive for its synoptic ability that, at the same time, conveys the emotion of bewilderment and lack of foresight that arises when, somewhere, the story takes a step forward.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the imposter team in the Tehran bazaar).
Too much action in too many places
The director had to accept the fact that an explained story doesn’t offer much in the cinematic sense of the most intriguing scenes.
Sometimes it adds something to reality: here everything doesn’t come out so elegantly (the scene in which the crisis lurks at the airport in Tehran, the deflection of a call to America and the unbridled search behind its track become madness).
Argo’s weakness is the lack of control that arises from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman have a very funny role as Hollywood collaborators, although their characters deserved more space and are by no means the only ones in this film.
For these reasons, Affleck’s film loses a bit of a dramatic streak, but it is a film that can be followed with moderate interest, valuing its realization and the retro style of a thriller that evokes the 70s.
But to collapse, that will be difficult.
As an evocation of a real history and as proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipresence and omniscience of the secret services can be, it is enough.
