Szabo: "The Germans must play a more prominent role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the admission of Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-European relations, this puts Berlin in a rather tricky diplomatic position.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany hinted that it would vote against the proposal to grant the Palestinian territories UN observer status.
However, Berlin eventually abstained.
Why is that?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not support what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
Now, because of the special relationship that unites the country with Israel, Germany must be careful.
But at the same time I don’t think it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without being overly critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained when it came to establishing a no-fly zone.
It has finally been declared by NATO.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear stance when important international issues are at stake?
Yes, it is.
This is because at the moment it is reorienting its foreign policy away from a policy led, so to speak, by the United States and focusing on a German foreign policy.
And what makes things even more difficult is that Europeans do not have a coherent and uniform policy.
The Germans are at a crossroads.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but are not used to doing so.
I think they are still groping about what their role will be, but they have already begun the path towards a “normal” foreign policy.
A foreign policy similar to countries like France or Great Britain.
What exactly does a “normal” foreign policy mean from the German point of view?
It is a policy that, when it comes to national interests, is willing to defend positions different from those of the United States or its European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy is strongly motivated by economic policy, i.e. exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are to some extent different from those of other great powers and for that reason Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the stance taken with regard to the conflict in the Middle East and the UN vote?
On the one hand, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf.
For this reason, it must be careful not to alienate itself from Arab public opinion and Arab elites.
This is important, of course.
But I would not give it so much importance since it is not a totally one-sided relationship.
However, they do play a fundamental role in German considerations.
Has Germany undermined its relationship with the US by refraining from voting on important decisions such as the vote on Palestine?
I think that in Europe, and even in the United States, the German position enjoys an enormous degree of understanding.
For this reason, I do not believe that there has been such a drastic rupture as in the case of Libya.
Germany may have earned some respect.
After all, all this has done is to show that it is a country that is taken seriously as an international actor and whose interests must be taken into account.
In Europe there are different opinions about the Palestinian initiative.
Instead, the U.S. has been clearly in favor of a veto.
Is there a disparity of opinion between the US and many European nations?
These disparities have always existed because of US domestic policy.
I think the Obama administration is secretly showing a great deal of understanding towards the European position.
But, because of the political situation here, it is clear that the government cannot defend this position in public.
I believe that the true disparity of opinions does not really have the magnitude attributed to it.
If we analyze the relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, we see that Obama is not at all enthusiastic about the policy he develops.
Is it difficult for Germany to reconcile its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of its main partners in the EU, on the other?
I think that is precisely what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a coherent and homogeneous European policy, but that is not the case.
Therefore, they do not have the possibility of being part of a higher entity, but they must push things from their own position.
That is precisely what they are doing now with the euro.
I believe that in the future Germany will take a leading role in forcing Europe to adopt a European stance.
Of course, this is not at all easy for Germany, either simply because of the relationship it has with Israel.
This has always been a tricky subject.
But I think the Germans are clear that they must play the role of an independent figurehead.
Does Germany see itself in the role of an important international actor? Does Germany really want to take on a leading role?
Or perhaps you still find it difficult to accept that leadership?
Germany is not yet used to it, it is always somewhat uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country still finds it difficult to play a more important role.
If we look at the euro crisis, for example, we see that every time Germany positions itself as the main actor, certain anti-German sentiments are unleashed.
This is not easy for the Germans.
This is an old problem and is that no one wants to be surrounded by enemy countries.
Seen this way, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
It must show a receptive attitude towards different neighbors and opinions and that is not easy.
The influence of the US in European politics is diminishing more and more, but the EU does not cover that gap at the moment, so who is left?
The Germans will have no choice but to assume a more prominent role.
Even if they don't like it, if they find it unpleasant or if it makes them an even more unpopular town, c'est la vie!
Stephen Szabo is Executive Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institution where academics and policy experts from Europe and North America jointly discuss the challenges facing the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he has specialized in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Brand protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese brands
Armani is a world-renowned brand and so is Polo Ralph Lauren.
What is Armani Polo?
Behind this name hides a name officially registered in China but that has nothing to do with the original companies.
However, it enjoys protection as long as the true eponyms do not file a claim.
And even then it is not clear that they will be given the reason.
“Foreigners find it increasingly difficult to protect their trademarks in China,” said Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing law firm specializing in protection rights violations in the Far East.
Every week a new case comes to my table.
Imitators simply add a couple of letters to be able to register their trademarks.
In this way, Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci and instead of Prada, Prada-Kny is registered.
German companies are also legally copied in the same way, as has happened to the sporting goods manufacturer Puma.
Pattloch opens a filing cabinet in which he keeps seats from the Beijing trademark office.
On 14 September 2010 a Chinese company applied to register the trademark Zegna DF Puma, an artificial name that was also used by the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
That the Chinese are world champions in copying and violating intellectual property rights is well known.
In the big cities there are department stores of several plants dedicated exclusively to the sale of counterfeits.
However, Pattloch’s cases are of a different nature: on behalf of his clients, he is fighting against the fact that the trademark office officially grants Chinese companies the right to take advantage of a name that is already registered elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "Bang Ming Pai" or accompanying mark.
The word has its origin in the Chinese term "Bang Dakuan",
It refers to women who have “fished” a rich man.
The Chinese government does not feel guilty.
“It’s detrimental to the business, you have to fight it,” Pattloch says.
"The brand makes water, the monopolistic position disappears and the damage to the image is enormous."
The financial losses and the procedural costs of the sectors concerned are multimillion-dollar, especially in the case of emblematic luxury products.
According to data from the market analysis company CLSA, with a volume of 15 billion euros per year China is, in size, the third market for luxury items and the fastest growing.
However, achieving the cancellation of registrations of dubious legality in the registration of trademarks is complicated and also involves a lot of money.
The process can take up to nine years and the outcome is uncertain.
Pattloch speaks of cases in which the court dismissed a lawsuit because so much time had passed that the name being sued had already become a “market reality.”
“If the plaintiff is unlucky, he may even have to pay the plagiarist money because the process has damaged the plagiarist’s brand in China,” Pattloch said.
Sometimes this is the law of the jungle.
Some of the best known cases have to do with graphic elements.
In 2009 Daimler-Benz lost a lawsuit against the construction machinery manufacturer Sany, the company that has recently been absorbed by the German concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
That’s why today the Chinese can still use an emblem very similar to the Mercedes star.
Volvo’s buyer, Geely, initially used a blue-and-white logo that was largely reminiscent of BMW; the matter was settled in court and Geely had to modify it.
The clothing manufacturer Lacoste lost in China to imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore whose logo represented a crocodile looking in the opposite direction to the original.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
The CTMO trademark office in Beijing acknowledges that in 2010 they have had difficulties due to a shortage of equipment and staffing.
Last year, however, “the work emergency situation returned to normal.”
In this way, the number of unprocessed claims processes has been reduced by 22%.
Almost 57,000 of these cases were resolved resolved, 75% more than the previous year.
However, 81,500 claims remain outstanding.
Fighting this costs a lot of money
As is often the case in China, the numbers are staggering.
Last year the CTMO registered more than 1.4 million trademark protection applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
This would be a new record and means that China leads the list of new entries worldwide for the tenth year in a row, according to the trademark office.
It seems that this also happens with the number of valid logos, a figure that amounts to 5.5 million in total.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan would have been pocketed in rights.
Put another way, this means that on average each registration costs 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
Fighting this costs a lot of money, as the case of the German family business Freudenberg shows.
For more than seven years the group has been fighting in court against a Chinese imitator.
While the Germans have managed to stop the illegal manufacture of imitation car parts,
the imitator has managed to secure the Chinese rights to the Freudenberg brand.
“We ourselves have caused this situation because in Germany surnames are not protected,” says Hanno Wentzler, President and CEO of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
The CTMO trademark office also dismissed the appeal of the Munichers.
In the next two instances they have agreed with Freudenberg, but the opposite side continues to fight today.
You have to be very careful
Now the case has reached the doors of the High Court of Justice, where it remains pending resolution.
Wentzler is confident that he can resolve the issue favourably and praises the professionalism of the courts.
However, he also states that “the procedure is extremely expensive, both in terms of money and time.”
It is difficult to estimate internal costs; the business archive has had to review files up to 100 years old in order to provide evidence.
Five years ago Freudenberg offered the opposing party a "six-figure sum in euros" with the aim of reaching an amicable settlement, but it was unsuccessful.
“This shows how much we care,” Wentzler says.
The dangers lurking in the Far East even threaten to affect Europe,
specifically if the imitators secure there the rights to unprotected marks.
Thus, a Chinese manufacturer tried to register in Germany the name Freudenberg for shoes and leather products.
The group has long since left this commercial field, but managed to prevent registration.
“You have to be very careful,” Wentzler says.
Both he and attorney Pattloch recommend that German companies be extremely cautious when doing business with China.
It is not enough to rely on international trademark law, but what must be done is "to register also in China everything that can be protected", as Wentzler points out.
Otherwise, the subject can be much more expensive than a simple registration.
In fact, should Freudenberg lose the last round of his particular battle, then he would have to pay the opposing party license fees for his own name, as Wentzler explains.
That or in the segment in question would drive us out of the market.
World AIDS Day: Dancing, Singing, Helping
Imbongi Choir Rehearses in Heidelberg, AIDS Orphans Rejoice in Swaziland
The story of a link capable of overcoming much more than 8,733 kilometers away.
First you start with the dance: cowboy boots, basketball shoes, high heels and moccasins look for the compass on the parquet floor, and they quickly find it.
One, two, three, four.
Only then do the singers’ voices slowly begin to rise (contralto, bass, tenor and soprano), swirling, numbing and following each other.
And Fiete Hopf, the 29-year-old director, threatens to almost get out of his box by trying to put order with his energetic and gentle gestures.
It is Monday afternoon and in the music room of the Institute of Medical Psychology in Heidelberg the choir Imbongi rehearses a new song.
The fifty singers, aged between 23 and 69, have also arrived, from the human geneticist to the master of the house.
"Om'Obani" is not an easy piece, each choir voice has a different text and also in a barely known foreign language: Zulu, a language spoken by eleven million people in South Africa, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique and in some areas of Swaziland.
Help for self-help
According to an estimate by UNAIDS, the United Nations AIDS programme, there are approximately 34 million people infected with HIV worldwide.
23.5 million of them live in southern Africa.
There are 245,000 AIDS orphans in Swaziland.
More than 40% of the population is already HIV-positive.
The Voices for Africa association has found sponsors in Germany for the 180 AIDS orphans of the village of Esitjeni.
Seventy of them attend high school.
For 15 or 20 euros a month you can sponsor a child.
This contribution will cover school tuition, uniform and will guarantee you a hot meal a day at the Gogo Center.
Imbongi means "storyteller" or "panegirist" in Zulu.
In this room, no one knows how to speak this Bantu language fluently, but they do know how to sing.
For ten years this choir has been rehearsing songs in this soft foreign language that sometimes manages to transport them to their place of origin: southern Africa.
8,733 kilometers away in a straight line from Heidelberg, in the northeast of the kingdom of Swaziland, there is a village called Esitjeni that depends on the voices of this German choir.
Forty percent are infected.
Approximately 2,000 people live there, some still in simple mud and straw huts, a large part of them children.
More than 300 no longer have parents because they have succumbed to AIDS.
Esitjeni is a small example of what affects Swaziland: the highest rate of AIDS infection and the lowest life expectancy worldwide, according to Unicef.
The population does not take kindly to circumcision, a practice that has been shown to halve the risk of contagion.
More than 40% of Swaziland’s inhabitants are carriers of the immunodeficiency virus, and dying at just over thirty has become commonplace.
During a joint trip to Africa in the spring of 2005 the choir discovered this hidden population, but what they saw above all were many children on the streets who lacked not only the protection of their parents, but the main thing: food, clothing and training.
Without a school diploma, the chances in a poor country are more than slim.
In the beginning it was only the particular commitment of a few that made it possible for a child to go to school and enjoy a hot meal a day. All this for a few euros.
However, a year later the choir founded the association "Voices for Africa" which since then has professionally cared for AIDS orphans in Esitjeni.
Facts about Sexually Transmitted Infections
What are the main sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STDs include syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
The most common STDs of viral origin are AIDS, human papillomavirus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Slats and scabies are among the STDs transmitted by parasites.
What are the main groups of people affected?
Syphilis and gonorrhea occur most often in men who have sex with other men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that at least four out of every five cases of syphilis recorded in Germany have their origin in sexual contact between men.
In the case of heterosexual adults, the most common sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydia, trichomonas, human papillomavirus, candidiasis (fungus) and gonorrhea.
HIV transmission among heterosexual adults in the country is relatively low; however, approximately 20% of new HIV infections occur in this group.
Among young people, chlamydia infections are much more common than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three-quarters of all infections affect young people between the ages of 15 and 25.
In our country, the human papilloma virus is also added to the most common diseases among youth.
How has the number of infections evolved?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to mandatory reporting.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of syphilis infections has doubled from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been on a downward trend since 2007.
Approximately 2,700 cases were reported in 2011.
This is one tenth less than in the previous year.
What symptoms indicate that it is a venereal disease?
Infectious diseases can cause sores in the genital area, discomfort when urinating, discharge, abdominal pain, as well as blisters or warts.
They often do not cause pain or other symptoms and are therefore not detected.
How can one be protected?
Condoms can reduce the risk of contagion, but they do not offer 100% protection.
Some pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted through dirt and physical contact infections.
For this reason, experts recommend regular medical examinations, especially if you change your sexual partner frequently.
If diagnosed early, most STDs can be cured and any late consequences can be avoided.
Through collaborations, donations and, last but not least, the fees that the choir charges for its performances throughout Germany, they come to raise quite a bit of money.
“In total, we have already sent some 200,000 euros to Esitjeni,” says Annette Lennartz, president of the association.
In the village itself, Zodwa Dlamini, a confident woman with leadership skills, manages the money sent from Germany.
She takes care that orphans find a good accommodation, for example with one of the grandmothers.
The "gogos", as older women are called in Zulu, are the pillars of the village.
Some of them have up to 14 orphans in their care, offer them a home to live in and ensure that children come to school every day on time and dressed in their uniforms.
Those who have no one are left under the protection of Khanyisile, a single woman who, like the two cooks who are in charge of cooking every day for more than 200 hungry children, receives a salary from the association.
In addition, "Voices of Africa" has set up a sewing school, built two chicken coops and, in collaboration with the American health organization PSI, has managed to get many of the inhabitants of the village tested for HIV.
This is not obvious, since, despite how obvious this disease is throughout the country, it is not usually spoken about openly.
A king with 14 wives
“AIDS is an absolute taboo,” says Annette Lennartz, “because it has to do with sexuality.”
Something strange in a country where the king officially has 14 wives.
The last absolute monarch of Black Africa, King Mswati III, is known for his opulent and over-indulgent lifestyle.
Polygamy instead of democracy.
This officially unaccepted way of life is largely responsible for the rapid spread that the HIV virus has experienced in recent decades.
But it is also due to the countless seasonals who travel the country from one side to the other and who take it wherever they go.
According to Annette Lennartz, “free condoms can be found in every corner, but they are hardly used.
It’s another culture, here they only accept skin-to-skin contact.”
To foster cultural exchange, the Imbongi choir travels every two to three years through southern Africa singing songs that speak of melancholy, fighting spirit, hope and confidence in the black race, songs that many in the southernmost tip of the African continent still remember from the apartheid era.
A bus full of whites singing songs in a black language; so much recognition not only brings with it an excellent atmosphere and a lot of joy, but it has also managed to wring a couple of tears from some rabid border soldier.
The trip always takes them to Ezitjeni, where the singers visit the sponsored children.
Although this small population hardly appears on maps, in the Ezulweni River valley it is well known.
"Draw closer to Esitjeni, there the light shines," says the locals.
And after traveling the 8,733 kilometers in a straight line back to Heidelberg to the rehearsal rooms of Bergheimer Street full of singers marking the passage, one realizes that it is also possible to see their light shine from there.
