It is a fact that, surprisingly often, the inhabitants of the region around Lerik often reach a biblical age.
There are currently 20 people over 100 years of age.
Why do so many elderly people live here in the south?
Azeri tour guide Farid Mugimzadeh explains that these are the special genes of the talyshis.
The director of the museum, Mrs. Fatulayeva, believes instead that the cause lies in food.
However, from a nutritional point of view, it does not seem logical that precisely the high-calorie diet of the Talyshi, who love meat, bread and especially dairy products and many of whom, in addition, drink a glass of melted butter daily, is so healthy.
Or is it perhaps the natural way of life that keeps people young? In Cengemiran, a small settlement not far from the town of Lerik lives Rubaba Mirzayeva.
At 97 years of age, he is relatively young for what is stylized by these latitudes.
Mirzayeva, who claims to have 143 children, lives in a simple wooden house typical of the entire Caucasus region.
Sitting on the floor, she tirelessly moves a huge tub of butter.
Eight people live under one roof, including one of Mirzayeva’s sons and a daughter, both of whom became grandparents long ago.
They also jump from one side to the other two small children.
In the kitchen they prepare tea for the guests, a tea that they serve in typical domed glasses.
Mirzayeva’s teeth are white and perfectly aligned and under the handkerchief she hides two long braids of dark blonde hair that her son proudly discovers for us.
I have always washed my hair with milk, so it has never fallen out and has maintained its color.
“I’ve never used a shampoo either,” says Mirzayeva.
The pension is enough to live on.
He has always eaten only what he produced on his own farm: tomatoes, potatoes and peas.
In all my life I have never been to a supermarket.
Then she tells us about her husband, who was in the army.
The worst was the post-World War II era.
However, everything went back to its course when the "dear father", Heydar Aliyew, took control of the situation.
This kind of propaganda sounds strange in the mouth of an older woman.
In Azerbaijan, however, the cult of the father figure of the nation, who runs his country like a dictator, knows no bounds.
He remained in power until 2003, when he gave the witness to his son Ilham.
At least the elderly people of Azerbaijan do not know what poverty is.
Mirzayeva charges 230 manat (about the same amount in euros) as a monthly pension, an amount with which one can live well considering the situation here.
And perhaps Mirzayeva’s gray-haired son is right: “in our culture the elderly are highly respected.”
They live in a big family, they are loved, they receive all the necessary care and they are happy.
As if this wasn't reason enough to stay alive for many years...
The term “human rights” is missing from the Constitution.
The revolution has returned to Cairo.
Demonstrations rivalling each other in Cairo underscore the country’s divisiveness.
The future constitution, with sharia law as its basis, is highly controversial.
The Egyptian president did not skimp on pathos.
“We have to get through the transition.
And for that to happen is my responsibility, to the people and to God,” he said on state television.
His speech was addressed to all the people, especially the Christian Copts, the liberals, the enlightened Muslims and the seculars.
All of them, hopelessly plunged so far into a confused opposition, are afraid.
Fear of a theocracy on the banks of the Nile by the grace of the powerful Muslim community.
As Mohammed Morsi explains, almost asking for forgiveness, he has had to temporarily annul the powers of the Constitutional Court and expand his own “in order to save the revolution”.
However, neither Egyptians nor the entire world know very well what this 61-year-old engineer with a PhD degree awarded by the University of Southern California really wants to save.
Do you intend to deprive the judiciary of its power?
In fact, the 234 articles, whose approval has been forced by a constituent assembly composed of 100 predominantly Islamist members in a 15-hour nightly meeting, are truly troubling.
As in previous constitutions, the draft also says that the jurisprudence is based on the "principles of Islamic law".
What do you mean by “principles”?
This was and remains open to interpretation and it seems that Islamists will take advantage of this vague formulation, as well as the legal leeway it carries, to impose a stricter interpretation of sharia.
This is at least what is suggested by a new article added: in all matters relating to sharia it is mandatory to consult Al-Ashar University, the most important Islamic institution in the country with great power in all Sunni Islam.
It doesn’t have to be that way, but this may mean that the clergy would control the legislation, something that – in fact – would result in the incapacitation of the judiciary.
Much of the draft constitution is open to interpretation.
What is also problematic is that it seeks to maintain military jurisdiction.
During Mubarak’s dictatorship these courts served to exert harsh repression on the opposition.
After the fall of the dictator up to 11,000 civilians were detained in military prisons.
As the draft states, the state must protect “the true essence of the Egyptian family” and “promote its morals and values.”
It is such an imprecise formulation in legal terms that with the help of this article state institutions could even control the contents of cinematography and literature.
To be clear, this is nothing more than censorship.
Of course, no article explicitly establishes equality between men and women.
On the other hand, another prohibits offending or slandering the Prophet Muhammad and his legates.
However, it is not clear what an offence is and how it should be punished.
Equally dubious is the wording that prohibits "offense to people"
Is a caricature of the president or a joke about a lawyer enough?
A question of interpretation, like many other things in the draft that has been submitted to Morsi for his signature and that, according to his words, "very soon" will be presented to the Egyptians to be submitted to referendum.
"The Revolution is Back"
For weeks the opposition has been closing ranks against the superiority of the Islamists.
Ten thousand people gathered in unusual harmony on Friday afternoon in Tahrir Square and vowed to scrap the act before it could take effect.
