The extension of Morsi’s powers to the three powers of the state caused this lawyer to resign.
The measures taken are flagrant violations of the rules of the democratic game and will lead Egypt to a new dictatorship.
“Instead of strengthening civil society, what the president has done is abolish it,” Saeda laments.
However, democracy cannot function without civil society organizations.
Saeda feels abandoned, also by the international community, which observes the ideological struggle that is taking place on the banks of the Nile with a mixture of curiosity and tension.
This could backfire on you.
A protester in Tahrir Square warns: “You are conceiving a monster that you cannot control.”
The Norwegian rakfisk: the smelliest fish in the world?
Norway’s five million inhabitants enjoy one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe but in the world.
Is it possible that the country’s success has anything to do with its avidity for an extremely foul-smelling fish?
Take a number of over-cured cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a mountain of dirty, damp football clothes.
Leave it there for a week.
Then you can smell the paralyzing aroma of rakfisk, one of Norway’s delicacies.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
The landscape is spectacular and that smell, always present, floats in the air.
The rakfisk is salted trout that is left to ferment in water for, depending on how foul-smelling you prefer it, up to a year.
As it gets darker and colder, Norwegians flock to a festival held here, in Fagernes, dedicated to this most, so to speak, captivating delicacy.
“You eat raw and then you drink a glass of aquavit from a drink,” says Havard Halvarsen, a city firefighter who is also known as the “Rakfisk General,” who is in charge of organizing the festival.
Everywhere we see people eating this fish that is kept in small cubes and drinking from a drink significant amounts of the drink.
“Some people like aquavit more than rakfisk,” says Havard.
Drinking can kill the smell.
I try some pieces.
If you can avoid passing it close to your nose, it’s not bad; it’s not much different than a portion of sushi that has traveled a few kilometers by bus.
Rakfisk is a product that comes from a very different time, in which poverty struck Norway and in which, before refrigeration existed, fish was kept during the autumn submerged in water and salt in airtight barrels.
Later, in the middle of winter, when it is already well fermented, it is taken out and, evidently with the senses inactive due to alcohol, it is eaten.
Just a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, and emigrated mainly to the United States.
Currently, the population is increasing rapidly; more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by the abundance of jobs, high wages and a complete system of social services.
A stream of Swedish people, the old rival and even not much richer than Norway, comes to this country to work.
Rakfisk is considered an important, if rather smelly, part of Norway’s past.
It is among the most expensive dishes you can buy.
But, in fact, everything is expensive. A cane of beer or a sandwich cost you a whopping 10€ ($14) each.
Norway does not usually appear on the international news agenda and most Norwegians like it that way.
Here people are still reluctant to pronounce the name of Anders Breivik, the far-right racist who shot and killed 77 people, including men, women and children.
Instead, they refer to the shooting as “the July 22 event.”
It is very hard for the Norwegians to believe that in their peaceful country one of their own was capable of committing such cruelty and murder.
Behind much of Norway’s current wealth is the growth, since the early 1970s, of one of the world’s largest oil and gas industries.
“But oil isn’t the only reason we’re doing so well,” says Anna, our waitress, as she passes rakfisk trays and, with her long blonde hair and striking blue eyes, represents the image of Norwegian well-being.
“We are, as you say, wise people.”
Her English, like most people in this country, is impeccable.
“We don’t like bragging, we don’t like ostentation.”
Norway has managed its oil wealth very cautiously; everything, except a small percentage of the money from this industry, is invested in a special fund for the benefit of future generations.
While everyone was wasting money they didn’t have during the years leading up to the worldwide financial crisis, Norway kept the wallet tightly closed.
“As long as we can ski in winter and hike in summer, we’re happy,” says Anna.
"And eat rakfisk," he adds with a cheeky laugh.
I’m in the snow queuing for something to eat; I’ve had enough rakfisk.
Now a moose burger is certainly something different and quite succulent to savour.
But at night, that stinky fish comes back.
The hotel I stay in is one of the many places where a rakfisk dinner is held in which diners vote for the best fish, or perhaps the one that most tests the nostrils.
A television has connected live with a presenter who wears a bow tie and is surrounded by dishes of rakfisk.
It looks like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"What are your scores for the best fish up there in the mountains, Thor-Juergen?"
"Here's our score, Havard."
There is laughter and applause.
A man falls from his chair, perhaps beaten by the aquavit.
Or maybe it's the fumes from all that fish.
Mexico: Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto faces a tough start
As Mexico’s incoming President Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant looks at the challenges the new president will face and the different expectations of his people.
Traffic in Mexico City is especially bad these days.
In a city that, in the best circumstances, is already congested, a steel fence has been installed since Monday that cuts several of the main roads leading to the city and is causing enormous chaos on the roads.
The aim, however, was not to prevent workers from reaching their workplace, but to prevent protesters from reaching parliament.
On Saturday, Mexico’s new president, Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto, will receive the presidential band and take over the nation’s management.
He faces a complicated task.
