However, her family believes her partner murdered her.
“When I arrived at his house, it seemed as if his body had been cleaned,” Ms. Buend<0xC3><0xAD>a recalls.
“There were signs that she had been beaten and rigor mortis had already appeared.”
As her mother recounts the story, a photograph of Mariana looks down from the walls, next to a cross that reads a single word: Justice.
However, that is exactly what the family says he has been denied.
“The state authorities have treated me as if I were an old gossip, a troublemaker, a complainer.
What they want is for you to just accept what they say and shut up.”
“But that can’t be the case when there have been so many irregularities and so much negligence,” he says.
The presidential band that President Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto will receive on Saturday will be accompanied by an enormous responsibility.
Tens of thousands of families have been affected by violent crimes in Mexico over the past six years and the new president has vowed to give them priority during his term.
“I hope he will be the same kind of president he was when he was governor,” says PRI deputy Olvera in Valle del Bravo.
However, that is precisely what the families of the victims of Ciudad Neza fear the most.
Bradley Manning did not report abuse, prosecutors say
Prosecutors try to address allegations of abuse by Bradley Manning during his time in prison
The trial focuses on Manning’s time in Virginia’s Quantico Military Prison.
The defense wants the case dismissed on the grounds that Manning's incarceration was severe.
The army soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
Prosecutors sought to prove Friday that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of confidential information in U.S. history, missed multiple opportunities to report the mistreatment he now alleges he suffered while in military detention.
During questioning of Manning at a pretrial hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Attorney General Commander Ashden Fein claimed that records of the weekly visits of unit officers Manning received during nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, show no complaints about his treatment.
The interrogation, which took place during a hearing following the defence ' s request that the case be dismissed on the grounds that his incarceration had been harsh and that it had already amounted to sufficient punishment, came a day after Manning had testified that he had planned to commit suicide while in detention.
The army intelligence analyst, arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents while on duty in Iraq.
Later, WikiLeaks published the material on the Internet.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of the information.
At Friday’s hearing, Fein reviewed with Manning the forms officers filled out after visits to Manning during his arrest at Quantico Military Prison, where he was held in maximum confinement from July 2010 to April 2011.
Officers would have asked Manning questions and written down his answers.
When Fein asked about the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he had called the treatment given to him by the caretakers “excellent” and the treatment received at the facility in general “very professional.”
The forms do not show any reports of ill-treatment, even though officers asked Manning directly about the treatment he was receiving, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed concern about some issues and that visiting officers had spoken to him about those issues and indicated that they would be dealt with, but that they had not recorded those issues in the register.
“They wrote ‘no issues’ (after I had talked about the issues) but this doesn’t necessarily mean I wouldn’t have mentioned any issues,” Manning said.
The judge, Army Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why she had not denounced the treatment she was receiving during the January 2011 meeting with a council tasked with examining suicide intentions that she had expressed on a form months earlier.
Manning responded that his intention during that meeting was to get the reduction of the “injury prevention” regime under which he was.
The military said it had put him under that restrictive regime, which is one degree below surveillance for possible suicide, to ensure his protection and the safety of others.
“I wanted the staff to know that I was okay and [wanted] to stop being under injury prevention ... so that I could enjoy what, in my view, is a better quality of life,” Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being moved to the military prison at the Marine base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he had considered suicide in Kuwait and on one occasion lost consciousness due to the heat.
He said that the fact that he was not allowed to know what was happening to him or what was happening in the outside world was very distressing.
“My world was reduced to just Camp Arafjon, to that cage,” Manning explained Thursday.
“I thought I was going to die in that cage.”
Manning claimed that, once moved to Quantico, he spent most days in a small cell, at least for 21 hours and often for 23 hours, unaccompanied.
Manning said he was only allowed to have a mattress, a blanket, flip-flops, some clothes and his glasses.
He explained that he tried to move all the time, as it was forbidden to sleep or even lie down during the day.
Manning claimed that he always had a light from outside pointing to his eyes as he slept.
He said that if the guards couldn’t see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up to turn around again.
Manning’s lawyer filed a formal complaint in January 2011 about Manning’s treatment.
Manning was transferred to Fort Leavenworth Military Prison in Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation she had made in Thursday’s statement that, after being forced one night to sleep naked in her Quantico cell, she was forced during a morning recount to stand naked in front of the guards and other inmates.
Manning had testified that he had never been given the opportunity to cover himself with the blanket during the recount.
During the judge's questioning Friday, Manning said she inferred from the watchman's order that she should drop the blanket she could have covered herself with, but acknowledged that no one had ordered her to drop it.
Manning testified Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because of an attempt to prove to an officer that he posed no danger to himself.
Manning said he had told the officer he could have used the elastic on his underwear or flip-flops to self-harm but had not.
Manning testified that his underwear, flip-flops and glasses had been removed from his cell that night.
His lawyers are hopeful that the judge will at least take into account the experiences he went through during his time in prison and drastically reduce his sentence should he be convicted at the court-martial, which is scheduled to begin early next year.
The defense said it plans to have Manning plead guilty to misdemeanors and defend other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is expected to resume this weekend and prosecutors are expected to argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon has maintained that Manning was held in accordance with the rules applying to any detainee who is in maximum custody in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include cooperating with the enemy, illegally provoking the publication of information on the Internet, leaking national defense information, and theft of property or public records.
If convicted of all charges, he could face life in prison.
My Mexican-American Identity Crisis
Says many were forced to leave Mexico due to lack of opportunities
Mexicans tend to criticize those who left; says they remember Mexicans from those difficult times
Navarrette comments that Mexican-Americans are caught between two worlds.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I had barely come down the esplanade and arrived at the immigration processing area and was already totally confused.
Signs showed the way to two queues: one for "Mexicans" and one for "Foreigners".
I sat there for a few seconds not sure where to go.
Growing up in Central California, I’ve been called “Mexican” all my life.
It’s ethnic shorthand, the same way my friends in Boston refer to themselves as “Irish” or my friends in New York call themselves “Italian.”
Later I decided on "Mexican-American".
But this was Mexico.
And, in my grandfather’s homeland, shorthand or scripts were not necessary.
He was simply an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to handle myself during an interview in this language.
But I don’t have the vocabulary level of a native and I can’t get rid of my American accent.
So I took my American passport and stood in line for foreigners.
I thought back to that moment this week when Mexican President-elect Enrique Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto visited the White House to meet with President Obama.
The agenda of the day, as always when the leaders of these two countries meet, consisted of: immigration, drugs and trade.
Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto was also keen to talk about the growth of the Mexican economy, one of the reasons why right now a Mexican is as likely to stay in Mexico as he is to venture to the United States.
It wants to partner with the United States and Canada and create a European Union-style trading bloc in North America.
In addition, Pe<0xC3><0xB1>a Nieto promised to continue fighting drug cartels in Mexico, although he did not give details.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is complicated and full of rancor.
Probably most Americans never remember that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to cede half of their territory at gunpoint.
But for Mexicans, who think in centuries, not minutes, the elements that remind them are everywhere.
So, the moment a U.S. official says anything that carries the slightest criticism of Mexico, you begin to hear complaints, both in the press and among the Mexican elite, about how Americans are usurping the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the sons of Moctezuma put themselves on a war footing.
And yet, for Mexico, the relationship that really is a challenge is the one they have with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans who live in the United States.
Are we talking about grudges?
There's a lot.
In Mexico there are winners and losers, people for whom the country provides opportunities and others for whom it does not.
The only reason there are so many people of Mexican descent living in cities like Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio is that, at some point in our family tree, there was a person, perhaps the father or mother or one of the grandparents, who was closed the door of opportunities in Mexico and had to march north.
And most of the time that person fit a certain profile: dark skin, a low level of education, coming from a poor town, etc.
We are their descendants and we are loyal to them.
Mexico is not.
And, even though we may be living the American dream now, having gone to good schools and had good jobs, we can never lose sight that what we are living is that, the American dream, and not the Mexican one.
Sometimes our identity may not be clear, but our loyalty is.
It's for the United States.
In addition, we are aware that many of the Mexicans belonging to the elite of the ruling class do not like us.
The feeling is mutual.
They see us as a reminder of a humiliating defeat and look at us over the shoulder as if we were from an inferior category that is not Mexican enough.
Our Spanish will never be good enough and our ties with Mexico will never be strong enough.
In their view, our existence is synonymous with failure.
If our families had not failed in Mexico, they would not have left.
And now we would not find ourselves trapped behind this silk curtain, living well in the United States but still as lonely souls.
My wife, who was born in Guadalajara and legally came to the United States as a child, reminds me that there is this friction between Mexicans and Mexican-Americans because the former know more solidly who they are and the latter this bothers them.
Although she is a citizen of the United States, she considers herself part of both countries.
Meanwhile, many Mexican-Americans I know feel they are not part of either.
We love to hear the Mexican group Los Tigres del Norte, but also Bruce Springsteen.
You have the best of each country, but you are not rooted in any of them.
In Mexico they see us as Americans.
In the United States, we are considered Mexicans.
Now, to further complicate matters, from what I have learned during my trip, some Mexican leaders and some intellectuals want to reconnect with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to work as improvised “ambassadors” of Mexico, representing their interests in the United States.
We would tell our fellow Americans how fantastic it is to visit that country and we would put pressure on political leaders to strengthen their ties with Mexico.
Yeah, sure.
That's not gonna happen.
There's too much rancor.
And, with wage inequality, rampant corruption and drug violence, many of us aren’t so sure it’s a fantastic country.
I'm afraid you're going to be left alone with this idea, friends.
That's fair.
If some Mexicans are still not prepared to forgive the United States for the way they treated Mexico a century and a half ago, then they have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans are still resentful of how their relatives were treated much less time ago.
Mm-hmm.
Maybe we're more "Mexican" than I thought.
Old battles, new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas may well be an unlikely basis for peace.
Will there ever be a lasting peace between Arabs and Jews in the Middle East?
Another bloodshed that seems to indicate that any hope is in vain.
Amid the useless and usual discussions about who started first, piles of buildings have been reduced to rubble; more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis have been killed and, for the first time, missiles from Gaza have fallen near Tel Aviv, Israel’s metropolis, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But, even though Israelis and Palestinians seem to be anchored in their old conflict, everything around them in the Middle East is changing.
The Arab Spring has left everything to pieces whether they like it or not, Palestinians and Israelis have been caught up in the regional uproar.
Perhaps this will make their struggle even bloodier than before.
However, there is reason to believe that their deadly stalemate could be unblocked.
A war that is neither lost nor won
At first glance, optimism currently seems very difficult to justify.
Even if the ceasefire agreed on Nov. 21 is maintained, this week’s clashes have bolstered hawks on both sides.
The leaders of Hamas, the Islamist movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will claim to have forced the Israelis to withdraw, even though Gaza has been badly beaten.
And despite having killed some of its leaders and pressured Gaza’s 1.7 million inhabitants into one of the most miserable and populated corners of the planet, Israel has not been able to put an end to Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining ground in the West Bank, the other part of Palestine currently ruled by its ruthless rivals from Fatah, the more moderate Palestinian faction.
