Generic tobacco packaging law goes into effect in Australia
Warnings about the risks of smoking and diseased body parts appear on green-off-white packets, which are the same for all brands of tobacco.
The Australian law on tobacco and generic packaging, a pioneer in the world, comes into force and replacing the logos and colors of the brands with a wrapper of a dull olive green, frightening images of body parts with diseases and representations of children and sick babies for being children of smoking parents.
With the exception of the various images and health warnings, the only difference between the boxes, mandatory since Saturday, are the names of the brands, all of them printed in a small font.
It is the world’s strictest regime applied to tobacco packaging.
The federal government of Australia claims that the goal is to deter young people from smoking by removing the traits that make this habit glamorous.
It relies on studies that show that if a person hasn’t started smoking before age 26, there’s a 99% chance they’ll never do it.
“You can see that children, even from a very young age, understand the message that the tobacco company is trying to sell through its brand,” said federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies showing, for example, how girls related the logo of a crown to the idea of being a princess.
Although Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and these changes will not affect the profits of multinationals too much, other countries are considering taking similar measures.
The tobacco industry has exerted enormous pressure against the law.
Tobacco companies said the law would encourage the black market in tobacco, in which cigarettes would be cheaper and more accessible.
“The legislation will have serious unintended consequences,” said Scott McIntyre of British American Tobacco in Australia.
The amount of tobacco that counterfeiters from China and Indonesia will bring to sell on the streets of Australia will increase.
Other people say their business has benefited from the passage of the law.
Sandra Ha, of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family-owned company, said the demand for silicone mouthpieces and covers to cover up nasty package images had skyrocketed almost from scratch two months ago, when British American Tobacco, Britain's Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost a challenge to the law in Australia's Supreme Court.
Ms. Ha said that Zico had sold up to 6,000 units to wholesalers and was expecting more stock.
“It’s a good business for us.”
According to experts, the possible obstacle is the popularity of social networks among the demographic sector to which the plan is directed.
Following a string of Australian laws banning TV advertising and sports sponsorship and forcing most retailers to keep cigarettes out of sight, tobacco marketing has moved online.
Australia has banned internet advertising to local businesses and websites, but cannot restrict it to foreign sites.
“If you market tobacco and you only have this small window left to promote your products, the online space is the most compelling place to be,” said Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman noted an increase in reviews of brands from “ordinary citizens” posted on social networking websites such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
One wonders if this is just a private citizen who really loves Marlboro cigars and has taken the trouble to make a video or if any marketing company is behind it all.
British American Tobacco of Australia said the industry is more focused on what the new rules mean than marketing.
The industry has even paid for Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to reject the new rules; these countries are claiming to the World Trade Organization that they are unfairly restricting trade, even though none of these countries has a significant volume of trade with Australia.
The WTO is likely to issue a resolution in mid-2013.
Plibersek said the government had held talks with other countries that are considering implementing similar tobacco packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada became the first country to introduce the requirement to include images in packages.
They are currently mandatory in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
In Britain, New Zealand, South Africa and India, tougher laws are being considered.
In Australia many smokers are defiant.
“Photographs don’t affect me.
I just don’t listen to them.”
"You take the cigar and you put the package away," Victor El Hage says as he buys a package with a picture of a tumor in its mouth.
“Honestly, there’s only one reason I would quit smoking: because of my daughter.”
James Yu, manager of the King of the Pack tobacconist in central Sydney, says that uniform boxes make it more difficult for him to place them on shelves.
“It usually took an hour to unwrap a delivery; now it takes four,” Yu says.
“The government should have banned tobacco altogether and then, that’s it, okay, it’s over and we close the shop,” he says as he raises his hands up.
In a constantly connected world, it’s not so bad to get a little bored.
During the Thanksgiving holidays this year, I unexpectedly had to spend five hours at an airport because the plane we were flying on suffered a mechanical problem and we had to wait for another plane to arrive.
So I had plenty of time to think about boredom.
I'm not gonna lie to you.
Spending half a day at an airport waiting for a flight to arrive is quite boring, even if you have the means to be entertained, such as books, magazines or iPhones, without forgetting duty-free shops.
But more and more academics and child development experts are praising the benefits of boredom.
According to them, it is okay that both we and our children get bored from time to time.
Getting bored forces the brain to look for interesting options and may encourage creativity.
Since most of us are currently connected to this or that screen, we don’t experience the benefits of boredom.
So, should we accept boredom in good spirits?
Oh, yeah.
And no.
But, we will talk about it later.
First of all, like many people, I assumed that now that we have more time for leisure, boredom would be a relatively recent phenomenon.
But, as Peter Toohey, a professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of the book “Boredom: A Lively History” published in 2011 by Yale University Press, says, this is not the case.
“In fact, the history of boredom is very long,” he says.
On the walls of Pompeii there are graffiti in Latin about boredom dating back to the 1st century AD.
We must also consider how we define boredom.
“The problem is that it’s already been defined and discussed in a variety of ways,” says John D. Eastwood, a professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After reviewing the published research and pitching the idea to a 100-person focus group, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of “desiring, but not being able, to engage in an activity that fills you up.”
The difference between boredom and apathy is that the person doesn’t do something but wants to do it.
He points out that with apathy there is no desire to do something.
The main experience of boredom, he says, is “the alteration of the process of attention, associated with a low mood and a feeling that time passes slowly.”
Boredom can sound terribly similar to depression.
However, Professor Eastwood says that although they may be related, people who are bored tend to see the problem as a matter of the environment or the world, while people who are depressed consider the problem to be theirs.
Sometimes we think we are bored, when what really happens to us is that we have trouble concentrating.
In his study “The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention,” published in the September issue of the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues referred to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape of a person reading a journal article.
Some groups listened in the adjoining room to a full-volume television program that had no connection, others listened to it with the volume low, so that it was barely noticeable, while the third group did not listen to the audio at any time.
The group that listened to the show with the low volume showed more boredom than the other two groups; they found it difficult to concentrate, but they were not sure why and attributed it to boredom.
“When you’re trying to focus on a difficult or interesting task, disturbance of attention can lead to boredom,” said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study’s authors.
“On the other hand, when you’re doing something boring, like spotting faulty parts on a manufacturing line, distracting music can help keep you from getting bored.”
“In fact, we currently know that moving or doodling, actions that are often interpreted as a sign of boredom, can actually help combat it, as they make that person more physically alert.”
“Research shows that those children who are allowed to move learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to be still,” says Professor Fenske.
We all know what it’s like to get bored at some point: the delay of a plane, a monotonous speaker, an especially boring movie.
But some people are more likely to get bored than others.
To help measure it, some researchers developed in the 1980s a “boredom trend scale.”
The scale includes questions like “many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous” and “there are so many things that interest me that I don’t have time to do everything.”
Stephen Vodanovich, professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, says that using such scales, researchers have found that boys are more likely to get bored more often than girls, and specifically need more external stimulation and more varied.
But, in general, teenagers are a type of group that gets bored quite easily.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and community development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day through a search.
It found that 32 percent of teens said they get bored while at school or doing homework, while 23 percent said they get bored when not in school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether the current boredom rates, 21 years later, would be higher or lower.
But he said what he did know was that “adolescence is a time when boredom is at its highest,” in large part because both kids and teens aren’t given a lot of control over what they want to do.
So, back to my question from the beginning: is it good to get bored?
Sometimes it is not, because, taken to the extreme, it can make us expose ourselves to absurd physical risks, such as betting or falling into the consumption of substances as a method to combat it, as research shows.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers talk about the connection between boredom and creativity, says Professor Vodanovich, who has been studying this issue for more than two decades.
“Boredom is the brain’s way of telling you that you should be doing something else,” says Gary Marcus, a psychology professor at New York University.
But the brain does not always know what is most appropriate.
If you’re bored and use that energy to play guitar or cook, that will satisfy you.
But if you watch TV, you may be satisfied in the short term, but not in the long term.
“So if your child is bored and you give them an iPad, they may not be bored anymore, but they won’t have learned to entertain themselves or dose themselves,” says Professor Fenske.
And “that ability to dose itself applies to other situations,” he says.
Not only does your child learn to entertain himself, but he learns to control himself better in other areas.
I don't think we really want to praise boredom.
But we shouldn’t be too critical of him either.
Our goal should be, rather, to feel comfortable away from the constant buzz of activities and technologies.
Professor Eastwood agrees.
"In our view, we need to get bored more, but boredom is a desire too distressing and disturbing to relate to something worthwhile," he says.
He points out that what people are really looking for is a way to disconnect and enjoy a dead time.
“In an environment where we’re constantly overstimulated,” he says, “it’s hard to find ways to focus our attention when the noise stops.”
Colorado: No Instruction Book for New Marijuana Law
Anthony Orozco, a 19-year-old community college student and soccer player from southeastern Colorado, is facing criminal prosecution for something that will soon be legal statewide: possession of marijuana stones and a pipe he used to smoke it.
Orozco says that one day in September, he and some friends were driving through Lamar, on the plains near the Kansas border, when police stopped them.
Police found marijuana in the car and some time later Orozco received a subpoena for possession of drugs and related items (minor offenses each carrying a $100 fine) informing him of the date of the trial.
“They treat us like criminals,” Orozco says.
And they are?
In the weeks of uncertainty following Colorado’s vote to legalize the possession of small amounts of marijuana for recreational use, the answer in hundreds of minor drug possession cases depends less on the law than on location.
Hundreds of misdemeanor marijuana possession offenses are being overturned both here and in Washington state, where a similar measure was passed.
Police departments have stopped bringing charges against those over the age of 21 for small-scale possession, which will be legally approved once the law takes effect in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors from Colorado’s most conservative districts have pledged to move forward with marijuana possession cases and are still subpoenaing people.
At the same time, several cities, from the suburbs of Denver to the western mountains, are voting to prevent newly licensed marijuana shops from opening in their communities.
“All of this is changing so quickly that I don’t know what’s next,” said Daniel J. Oates, police chief in Aurora, just east of Denver.
Those in charge of regulations in Washington state are also turning the issue around.
And they continue to seek advice on establishing a system of production, manufacturing, distribution and sales licences, all before the deadline of 1 December 2013.
They say that, for better or worse, Colorado is ahead of most states in regulating marijuana use, first for therapeutic purposes and now for recreational use.
“Colorado has a more regulated market, so it will be a good guide,” said Brian E. Smith, a spokesman for the Washington State Alcohol Control Commission.
But Mr. Smith admits that any place or system can only make suggestions about what might work.
“There is no real precedent that serves as a model for us,” he says.
The Washington law, called I-502, takes effect on December 6, which also leaves a year during which you will swim between two waters, since the licensing system in that state will not yet exist, but the possession will be legal.
In addition, there are some delicate mechanical issues that need to be resolved during that period, such as how to maintain a balance between the state’s requirement to provide “adequate access” to licensed marijuana and its prohibition of conducting cannabis businesses within a radius of less than 300 meters from schools, parks, playgrounds or children’s centers.
“Nowhere will it be more difficult to locate a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, especially in the greater Seattle area,” says Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a newly created research group.
On November 21, Aurora police chief Oates sent an email to his police officers informing them that the city prosecutor would stop prosecuting people over the age of 21 for minor marijuana possession offenses and that the police would stop bringing charges against those offenses “with immediate effect.”
Police Chief Oates said they would enforce city regulations regulating the cultivation of marijuana for therapeutic purposes and would continue to pursue drug dealers and sellers.
In Weld County, in northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck represents a stricter view.
After the vote, he said his office would continue to prosecute marijuana possession cases, mainly to pressure consumers to decide to receive treatment.
Currently, 119 people face charges for possession of 56 grams or less of marijuana, although many of them have other charges.
“Our office has an obligation to bring legal action against those offenses that at the time they occurred were offenses,” Mr. Buck said in a statement.
The response has been complicated even in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected the marijuana legalization initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the county’s largest city, no longer cite adults for possession of small amounts.
Pete Hautzinger, the county district attorney, supported this decision, but also decided not to dismiss any of the pending possession cases.
"I don't think he's wasting his time in continuing to enforce the law until it changes," he said.
Even though 55 percent of voters supported the measure, it was never considered that bringing recreational marijuana use into the government and judicial system would be easy.
The contradictory reactions that arise throughout the state show a marked ambivalence among officials regarding the great ecological experiment in this state.
“It’s a cultural barrier with district attorneys,” says Sean McAllister, a Denver attorney who represents marijuana possession defendants and is a local spokesman for the National Organization for Marijuana Law Reform.
“They’ve spent so much time taking people to court that they can’t really accept that it’s legal yet,” he said.
As the first states to consider small amounts of marijuana in the same way as if it were alcohol, Colorado and Washington are preparing to become national test cases for drug legalization.
While attorneys and state officials have a new frontier of legal sales, they also look forward to receiving directions from the federal government, which still envisions considering the sale and cultivation of marijuana as federal crimes.
Advocates of marijuana legalization are hopeful that the Justice Department will yield.
Although there have been some notable arrests of patients and sellers of marijuana for therapeutic purposes, the federal government has mostly allowed marijuana businesses to exist in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states.
“While anti-drug agents are unlikely to pull down doors to confiscate a small bag of drugs, they will likely be reluctant to allow the operation of state-regulated stores for the sale of marijuana for recreational use, permitted under the new law,” said Kevin A. Sabet, a former Obama administration drug policy adviser.
Several Colorado cities are not waiting for federal authorities to act.
Even before Election Day, some local governments approved moratoriums on any new marijuana stores, even though it will be about a year before any of them can open.
Last week, the western city of Montrose adopted a six-month ban and is likely to pass it next week.
“We don’t want to put ourselves in a situation where we authorize someone and then have a serious problem at the federal level,” said Bob Nicholson, a city council member.
“Our community voted against this amendment.
We are studying what the community voted for versus what the state voted for.”
A lot of questions arise about this.
Petronella Wyatt: 'I was bullied out of Oxford for being a Tory'
Don’t attack college students for their views just now
I don’t remember a time in my life when I didn’t dream of getting a place at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother had been in what I assumed was the best place in the world to learn, a contemporary-era Greek symposium that fostered the two pillars of civilization: free thought and tolerance.
However, within two weeks of taking my place at Worcester College in the late 1980s to pursue a career in history, I had already packed my bags, which triggered the first scandal of my life.
My father collapsed and began to cry.
My friends were baffled.
The Evening Standard newspaper claimed that I had quit because I did not tolerate some college classmates having sex in the next room.
The writer A. N. Wilson jokingly announced that I had left because I was being forced to drink from peeled cups.
The truth was less fun.
I ran away from there.
Yes, I fled, because I had been subjected to systematic harassment and intimidation.
Not because of my fancy name, or the fact that I came from a private school.
I was harassed for only one reason, which in the cradle of the supposed illustration was somewhat intolerant and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a leading adviser to Margaret Thatcher and I supported the Conservative party.
You may be wondering what this is all about now.
Well, several reports indicate that a new generation of center-right students is suffering similar persecution.
The institutionalised and growing hatred of Conservative party students is such in Oxford that, last week, a group of them claimed the same level of equal rights as homosexuals, the disabled and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of Corpus Christi College's JCR say they are "often seriously sidelined, personally attacked, and treated like unappreciated people" for their political views.
They want to create a position on their college’s equal opportunity committee to make sure they can express their opinions freely.
Their plight was not helped by a recent BBC2 documentary called "Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right" about student politics that portrayed the Tories as eccentric and neo-Nazi.
It showed graduate student Joe Cooke, former chairman of the Oxford University Conservative Party Association (OUCA), in a Rolls-Royce, wearing a silver suit and a cane with a silver handle.
At other universities, conservative students say they are treated as “Turkish heads” by the introduction of higher tuition fees.
Luke Black, a 20-year-old vice-president of the University of Nottingham’s Conservative Party Association, told a Sunday newspaper that “there is a growing trend of leftists in universities.
People assume we’re like the Bullingdon Club without even knowing each other.”
Samuel Roberts, a 21-year-old history student in Corpus Christi who filed the motion for greater protection, says this environment is “uncomfortable,” while Stephanie Cherill, a 19-year-old and OUCA president-elect, says the attitude of JCR members toward people who are center-right has worsened.
“This poses a threat to the environment of intellectual debate, as well as to the well-being of members,” he says.
During my first few weeks at Oxford I was more alone than one.
I entered college in September 1986, I was a terribly shy 18-year-old.
Hatred towards the Conservative Party was at its highest.
The previous year, the university had voted to deny Margaret Thatcher, a former student, an “honoris causa” degree following cuts in higher education funding.
The atmosphere would have made any Stalinist shudder with horror.
Already during the first days of the week of welcoming the new university students, when the new students meet and know the professors, I received a sample of the bitterness that awaited me.
I found that professors not only turned a blind eye to the mockery of conservative college students, but willingly participated in it.
The politics of the miners’ strike, privatization, and government opposition to anti-apartheid sanctions in South Africa reached as far as the seminary’s wooden halls.
The first one I attended had to be translated into English French texts of the eighteenth century and I was not prepared for what came next.
"Miss Wyatt," said Professor Harry Pitt (now deceased), "please translate the first paragraph."
Not one of them.
Pitt, a short man with a face that looked like cake dough, knew well how to expel mala bile.
“Do the Thatcherites refuse to learn French, or are they just fools?” he asked.
The other students laughed.
My eyes were burning with the tears I was trying to hold back.
“I suggest you go to French classes in your spare time, as long as you’re not too busy meeting people,” Pitt growled.
I returned to my room as a soul in grief.
That night I sat alone at dinner time in college; then I felt a slight pat on the back.
He was a second-year English student named James who introduced himself as a member of the OUCA.
“I know who you are,” he said kindly.
“I’m afraid that’s how it goes.
They mess with anyone who's suspected of being Tory.
For me it's very complicated, but they know that your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so for you it will be even worse.
Many newly arrived Tories appear to be Labour.
Later, in a local pub, I tried cowardly to hide.
I insisted that I disagreed with everything Mrs Thatcher said.
That trick was useless.
A freshman in Philosophy, Politics and Economics who, paradoxically, had studied at Eton, said: “You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You're contaminated."
Other students adopted that song.
I became the dirty pervert.
“How do the Tories have sex?” one asked.
“They beat each other up, don’t they?”
I felt the same way that homosexuals should have felt before the liberal law of the 1960s.
Could he one day lead a normal life in Oxford?
Would I be forced to stay with people who think like me only after dark?
Should I become a laborer and repress my natural tendencies?
The three years that awaited me presented themselves as a purgatory of ostracism and isolation.
The only openly Tory professor was Norman Stone, Professor of Contemporary History assigned to my college.
He was hated for being not only a Conservative, but also a foreign policy adviser to Thatcher and one of the people who wrote her speeches.
He was barely there.
He detested the place because he considered it provincial and insignificant and because of its adherence to the Marxist-determinist view of history.
In 1997 he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
“You’re not going to be happy here,” he said.
I began moving daily from Oxford to my parents’ home in London, finding refuge in my more open-minded metropolitan family and friends.
I told my father I hated Oxford and why.
She didn't believe me.
When he studied there in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
“But it’s the best place in the world,” he said sadly.
“They would never do that, not there among my beloved dream needles.
Even my communist friends have always had an impeccable attitude."
His aching eyes began to cloud.
“Give him another chance.
I'm sure they did it just to joke.
It would break my heart if you left it."
Exhausted from so many trips to London, my emotional stamina was deteriorating.
A friend of mine, who also supported the Conservative Party, had succumbed to pressure and renounced his creed.
The following week, during a seminar in which another professor of History had hinted, quite seriously, that I was an “enemy of the people,” I decided to do the same.
Red with shame inside, I admitted that my parents had “brainwashed” me and called them “stupid old men.”
The truce lasted only a short time.
It was my father who put the last nail in the coffin of my college career at Oxford.
At that time my father wrote two weekly columns in Murdoch’s press.
My door was locked.
I was inside huddled in fear and, after five minutes, my pursuers gave up.
When they left, I packed my bags and took the first train to London.
I never came back.
Maybe you call me a weak crybaby.
But no 18-year-old should be subjected to such a level of intimidation and hostility in an educational institution.
What is even more tragic is that it was Oxford, which not only trained 14 Conservative Party prime ministers but, to this day, hides behind an undeserved reputation for equality and freedom of thought.
"Valentino prefers elegance to notoriety"
On the occasion of the exhibition "Valentino: Master of Sewing", which opened this week in London, ABC talks to Naty Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza and other famous clients of the Italian designer
Somerset House, former residence of Elizabeth I of England, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition on Valentino Garavani.
The designer has recognized it during the inauguration of "Valentino: Master of Sewing", an apotheosisic retrospective that brings together more than 130 haute couture dresses created by his "maison" during the last 50 years.
“I love this palace,” he says with his unmistakable Italian accent.
This exhibition is the culmination of a story whose only protagonist is "il Signore" Garavani, but which could not have been written without his distinguished clients.
Valentino has always been fascinated by the rarefied and distant world of nobility.
In the first room of this exhibition, open until March 3, private letters and photos abound with the signature of the most garnet of the aristocracy, from Princess Salimah Aga Khan to Lord Snowdon, through Princess Marie-Chantal of Greece and Margaret of England.
Valentino teaches those personal memories as trophies of his social ascent: from humble couturier in the northern Italian town of Voghera to idol of the international jet-set.
Being in love with royalty has nothing to do with it.
“At least they don’t turn off their cigarette butts on your magnificent carpet like some beautiful pop music celebrities do,” says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza.
In the 60s and 70s, we both lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is a spectacular host and entertains with generosity and elegance.
“We all loved being invited to their chalet in Gstaad,” explains the ex-wife of “Heini” Thyssen, intimate of forgotten beauties like Marella Agnelli or Eugenie Niarchos.
Valentino has always preferred elegance to notoriety.
And yet, she's a star.
Valeria Mazza, wearing a Valentino
The Argentine model Valeria Mazza also does not forget the charisma of the couturier.
Many years ago, after a parade in Piazza di Spagna, in Rome, we went to his apartment for dinner.
We were twenty people, including Sharon Stone and John Kennedy Jr.
In every detail of the floor, the decoration, the food, the music, in everything his spirit was seen and felt.
“Each of the guests made us feel important and loved,” recalls the “top model,” who began working with him during Paris Haute Couture Week in 1995.
“It never goes out of style because their designs are works of art,” he concludes.
Parade of Alcurnia
