The Toughest Job in the World: Kawah Ijen's Human Mules
For four euros, the porters of the Indonesian volcano risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilos of sulfur through steep stone paths
There are people for whom their work is hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who make a living extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
To do this, it has to descend every day to the bottom of its crater, where the sulfurous gas emanating from the bowels of the Earth solidifies when it comes into contact with the air.
After tearing off large sulfur rocks, which in total weigh about 70 kilos, he carries them in two baskets of bamboo that he carries on his shoulders through steep stone paths.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises to 2,386 meters above sea level, but the exhausted porters take more than 40 minutes to ascend at turtle pace, keeping the balance and carefully measuring their steps so as not to slip and fall down the precipice.
They know that any misstep could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell off the cliffs of Kawah Ijen years ago.
Kawah Ijen miners earn 5 euro cents for every kilogram of sulphur they extract
Once up, they make their way among the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus monkeys and, tiringly carrying the heavy baskets, they walk three kilometers to the scale that a mining company has placed a little lower, at 1,850 meters high.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been exploiting the volcano since 1960 and, never better said, its workers, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents) for each kilo of sulfur.
It is then sold for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to the petrochemical industry, as this mineral is widespread in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
“As it is normal to carry 70 kilos, we take out about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip,” explains Anto, who usually makes three deliveries daily.
It takes three hours in each and ends up ground, but they allow you to gather 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems a misery for such inhuman effort, it is triple what you would gain on the field.
“The miners’ wage is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid at 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly salary is two million rupees (167 euros),” clarifies the porter, who previously worked as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the stake was not so hard, but Anto has returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as forceful as sulfur: "I married a young woman from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her to Java to convert."
Anto has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly, and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases
At 27 years old, Anto has been playing the skin in the Kawah Ijen, whose sulfur has already begun to take its toll despite covering his face with a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases released by the volcano.
It’s the price you have to pay to get your dream.
“I will work two more years because I want to open a store or study Spanish or French,” he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished for life, this friendly and intelligent young man could be a tour guide, waiter or hotel receptionist, but instead he does the work of a mule.
Sharing a filthy wooden cabin with other porters, he gets up every day at two in the morning because the sulfur does not stop flowing at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the middle of the darkness.
Defying the shadows, Anto descends into the crater lighting himself up with a small flashlight attached to his helmet, which he himself has bought with his money.
About 400 porters carry the sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the crater.
Despite its benefits, the mining company has not mechanized the extraction of sulfur to save costs or provides any equipment to the porters, who work on their own and at so much the weight.
In fact, they do not even see part of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) of surcharge per camera that, along with the entrance of 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros), the guards of this natural park charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human mules.
“This job is for the beasts and not for the people,” said Madrusin, a 42-year-old porter who has been at Kawah Ijen for three decades since leaving school.
Able to lift up to 110 kilos, he says he will endure working "as much as he can" because he needs the money to educate his three children, between 18 and 10 years old.
I won't retire, I'll die here because the volcano has been my whole life
Although the sulfur burns the throat and darkens the eyes when the wind suddenly changes and traps the miners in the thick columns that come out of the volcano, they are so hard that no one complains of suffering from serious diseases ... beyond, of course, their usual breathing problems, osteoarthritis, knee pains and shoulder sores, which have been malformed by the weight of the baskets.
Swinging the basket on his back, Unainik can now only carry 50 kilos at the age of 53.
Each day, he and his companions blast 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks move to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away on a goat path through the undergrowth.
“I will not retire, I will die here because the volcano has been my whole life,” Unainik proclaims, opening his mouth wide, where he is missing several teeth.
Of his five children, the eldest, aged 30, also works carrying sulfur.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the hardest trades in the world: that of the human mules of Kawah Ijen.
Singapore looking for babies to save economy
Singaporeans blame career, stress and the cost of property and education for not having children.
“The population of Singapore needs to grow.”
I am a patriotic husband, you are my patriotic wife, let us fulfill our civic duty and believe life!
It may seem implausible that these verses are part of a peppermint pill ad, but despite that — or perhaps because of it — the video went viral on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The phrases are part of a rap that uses local references such as "Let's put a bao (bun) in the oven" to laugh at Singapore's birth rate.
The advertising company that made the video, BBH, is hoping that with the announcement they will be able to draw attention to the problem in a fun way.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, says he wanted to use the power of music to get people to do “their national duty.”
This is purely an internet thing, so we had to make it fun and funny.
This is the biggest problem in this country.
We are the worst in the world at reproducing ourselves, so we felt this was a topic we had to address.
We knew that the government had tried many things, such as launching perfumes with pheromones or organizing speed-dating evenings.
Many of those ideas may have been creative, but they didn’t necessarily work.
So we thought, why don’t we do as creatively as possible to solve this problem, which is to compose a rap?
1.2 children
The one who doesn’t take it so lightly is the Singapore government.
It spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
A government package for marriages and parents grants up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all this has had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and its strict social controls.
Singapore's birth rate, according to its national population division, currently stands at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2 – known as the replenishment rate – was in 1976.
So why don't Singaporeans have any more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of marriage and family policy at the National Population Division, says it’s because of a “better education” and “a wider range of career opportunities.”
“That has allowed people to have a wider range of choices in terms of life goals and priorities, beyond getting married and starting a family,” she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to increased singleness, and delayed marriage and births, resulting in a decline in the birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, an immigration policy aimed at dramatically increasing immigration to cope with the declining population has created resentment among the local population.
In Singapore, there are websites where barely disguised xenophobia abounds against many new immigrants, particularly the Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and not integrating.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why last year Singapore’s ruling party experienced its worst election result since independence.
Since the elections there has been an attempt to correct the problem, with higher quotas and levies for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the fall in the birth rate has known effects on a nation’s economic growth, tax revenues, health costs and immigration policies, Singapore’s example is also having some unexpected consequences.
The government is trying not to build so many small houses.
For example, it has begun to affect the real estate sector.
The urban development authority has moved to control the number of small apartments, known as shoeboxes, that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and have been very successful in sales.
However, there are concerns that they may promote a singles lifestyle and discourage developers who want to build large, family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, CEO of real estate firm EL Developers, says his “shoe boxes” sell much faster than larger units.
They are more popular, in the sense that units run out days, even weeks, faster than larger units.
This makes it much better for our cash flow.
However, he admits that the new rules give clearer guidance to developers, who were previously hampered if they wanted to offer too many small units in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city state.
While these new rules may be a step toward raising the national birth rate, talking to Singaporeans working in the downtown financial district looks like they’re not going to have much of an effect.
“People are very stressed, houses are expensive and so is education, so a lot of people are putting it off,” says one young executive.
Other people may have children.
“But for me it’s important to have my own money and time,” says another young man in his 20s.
Men and women cite their careers, stress, and the cost of property and education as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So, no matter how much the government tries to push its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, Singaporeans have the last word.
Private Offline is Private On Line
Privacy.
According to the Dictionary of the Royal Spanish Academy it is about the quality of private or "the sphere of private life that one has the right to protect from any intrusion".
What is private for a child under 16?
How do you apply this definition in your daily life and on social media?
Do you understand the dangers to which you are exposed by airing situations on the Internet that you would surely not share offline?
The newspaper interviewed five boys between the ages of 10 and 15 who were frequent users of the network.
In four of the cases, they associated the term with “something very mine,” on a personal level, and “in the user’s key and name,” when they applied it to social networks.
“My deepest secrets wouldn’t be uploaded to a post,” says Jorge, 10, as he tries to explain the meaning of private on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
