In FB I upload beautiful images or games.
I also have fun with my acquaintances.
“I wouldn’t share a picture that’s not mine, or someone who’s making a fool of themselves,” he says.
The child recognizes that it is wrong to post obscene photographs, of naked people, of crimes or write humiliating or violent comments.
Jorge claims to know the 35 friends he has on FB and his nine followers on Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
The mother is included, she has the key to one of the accounts.
I opened Twitter to express myself and write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if they answer me, I just upload them," he adds.
“Social media is entertaining, I can talk to distant relatives or my friends quickly,” he says.
He does not hesitate to answer that he would never accept a request from an unknown person.
I wouldn't listen to anyone recommending you to a stranger.
The case of 14-year-old Jose is different.
The teenager has open accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, in the latter admits not knowing 20 of the people added to his list of friends.
“It doesn’t scare me, because we have something in common, music for example,” he says.
According to the boy, no one has hinted at him or asked for his home address or phone number.
“If they pressured me or demanded it, I just take them out of my account,” he said.
José became a follower of Ask, after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
The boy is no stranger to the experiences of what is now known as cyberbullying.
