“I never knew who he was,” he says.
The victim, according to Jose, did not close the account.
“It just gave him privacy.”
It then explains a series of steps to set up the account securely.
Unlike Jorge, this guy would upload photos of acquaintances in uncomfortable or embarrassing situations.
Yes, I would, if I don't like it or if I feel like it.
“Even though I know that’s cyberbullying,” he says.
Key Questions
Marielos Porras, English teacher and graduate in Education and Learning, believes that to guide children and adolescents must be understood that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
“The Internet emerged as a means of searching for information, but with the emergence of these sites the rules of the game changed,” he says.
Porras points out that academician Marc Prensky, master’s degree in Pedagogy from Yale University and author of the work Natives and Digital Immigrants, coined these terms to explain the phenomenon.
The digital natives are them, the children and young people who were born with the technology.
“We’re the digital immigrants that we have to teach them, when we’re still learning,” he says.
He comments that the issue is complex, "because we are asking them to have a defined criterion on what it is appropriate or not to disseminate, publish or say at an age that maturity does not give for that."
“Also be selective when what matters most to them is being popular, having thousands of friends without thinking about the consequences.”
According to the specialist, the most effective way to teach children and adolescents what privacy is is through questions that make them reflect.
