There are things you wouldn’t tell a stranger, why do you do it on the Internet?
Or, would you like them to post a picture of you like the one you posted about a friend?
Do you know what others post about you?
When you tag party photos, did you ask other people’s permission to tag them?
And one more thing, does everyone need to know what you’re doing every moment?
Another point is to make them see that they must act online as they do offline.
It's the same rules.
“One off the internet acts with respect, morality and other principles, the same should be true on social media,” he says.
Vigilance
Estuardo Guardia, university professor, primary school teacher and educational consultant, comments that it is essential that parents read the policies of social networks.
By understanding each of the sections, they have a solid foundation to talk to their children about the implications of opening an account on the Internet.
“For example, age and what is allowed to be shared or posted,” he says.
According to Guardia, it’s key to remind children of the “don’t talk to strangers” lesson.
UNASUR Summit ends without making the Lima Declaration public
The VI Presidential Summit of the South American Union of Nations (UNASUR) concluded today in Peru without making public the Lima Declaration, previously announced and theoretically signed by the seven attending presidents.
Efe repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VI Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of UNASUR, but sources from the Foreign Ministry and the Presidency indicated at the beginning that they were going to deliver it after the closure, but later stated that at some point it will be published on the website of the Peruvian Government.
When consulted by the text, they pointed out that the content had been exposed by the president of Peru, Ollanta Humala, during brief statements to the press.
Journalists’ access to Summit information was restricted at all times.
During the day, only the video without sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The little information that circulated among the reporters was delivered by the press spokespersons of some of the governments of the UNASUR attending the meeting, although not the Peruvian.
The only document released during the day was the list of attending presidents, which caused the discomfort of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media asking for more data.
Subsequently, the Presidency of Peru sent an email to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it is about Humala's pronouncement, and not the official document that closed the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third South American-Arab Summit (ASPA), and on that occasion, despite being insistently requested by the press, the so-called Lima Declaration that they had previously announced was not disseminated either.
On the official website of ASPA it can be corroborated that the document was published last Tuesday.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities made every effort to ensure that transmission systems were in place for all journalists, but limited the collection of information as much as possible.
The summit also concluded with a joint commitment by Chile and Peru to accept a ruling by the Hague Court that settles a border dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era, met during the regional meeting and ratified that they will respect the decision of the (ICJ), which begins Monday in The Hague to hear the arguments of both parties, in the process that Lima presented against Santiago.
“We will abide by and execute the sentence that defines the differences that we are bringing to this international court today,” said Humala, together with his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has been, is and will continue to be a country respectful of international law, the peaceful settlement of disputes, treaties and international courts," Pi<0xC3><0xB1>era added, shaking hands with Humala, next to the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation of both presidents that they will submit to the ICJ came after Colombia denounced this week the Bogotá Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the rulings of that international court, after a decision on maritime limits with Nicaragua that it considered seriously wrong.
The summit was attended by the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the dismissal of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was in charge of opening the deliberations in the morning and closing the summit, shortly after noon in Lima.
The president read the final document in which he reported that 16 agreements were adopted and the lines of action were set for 31 projects between the South American countries for a total of 17 billion dollars in investments.
Among the agreements adopted he mentioned that the countries of UNASUR will take "important steps towards the goal of a South American citizenship for which we are expanding the agreements on residence".
He reported that actions are being promoted to improve "cooperation in the fight against citizen insecurity and against transnational organized crime, actions to make medicines more accessible, low-cost internet access in all corners of South America, and jointly and efficiently address the risks of natural disasters."
With a Europe in crisis, “the economic consolidation (of Latin America) should not have a triumphalist matrix but should serve to expand our productive matrix and envision a better future for our peoples,” Humala added.
“We have decided to privilege a group of 31 emblematic projects that will improve the connection of the spaces of South America, especially in rural and border areas ... uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits,” the Peruvian president said in a message read.
Among those projects, he mentioned that five correspond to Peru, and are located in the transversal axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two point to a greater connection with Ecuador, although he did not give greater details.
The final document also mentioned the political situation in Paraguay.
“We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve to rejoin the Union of South American Nations,” from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated, and good relations between neighbors, was another of the issues highlighted by the summit.
In this sense, the president of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before starting his participation in the regional meeting that he hoped to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico to treat in a respectful way the maritime dispute after a ruling of the ICJ, questioned by Bogotá.
“Tomorrow (Saturday) I may have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega,” Santos said.
“We will review all these paths, they are not exclusive, even the treaty with Nicaragua will require a conversation with Nicaragua,” he stressed.
“With President Ortega, I hope to be able to tell him that we will handle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible,” Santos said.
