AIDS deaths today are cause for late detection
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed to have the test result: AIDS positive.
“It was as if I dropped a bombshell,” he says, recalling the moment of the announcement, which the doctor tried to make “smoother,” with no obvious success.
The boy hid it from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to learn about it; with such determination that he already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is, without a doubt, one of the oldest patients of the HIV Unit of the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), which he arrived in 1994 after several battles.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something difficult to imagine in the early 1990s, when there were many doubts, few treatment options and more stigma.
Then, even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye to him “because he brought a cut.”
AIDS was synonymous with death.
It is now possible to survive this syndrome and do so with quality of life.
